INSERT INTO `earth_posts` VALUES (309, 3, '2009-11-16 11:43:47', '2009-11-16 10:43:47', '<p style="float: right; margin-left: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px"><a title="Shed Roof Repair by warriorwomen, on Flickr" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/warriorwomen/4106881738/"><img src="http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2726/4106881738_0bcd2d864b_m.jpg" alt="Shed Roof Repair" width="180" height="240" /></a></p>A post storm reccy lead to an altercation of sorts between the lazy starter-leaver (me) and the task focused, completer-finisher (Lynn). The wind had completely denuded the shed of its patchy roofing felt but with only 15 mins allocated for the plot visit there was never going to be time enough for a full repair job. \r\n\r\nI was of the view that without a hammer, a ladder, the time, the inclination or the right clothes, we should put the soon to be rotten shed roof to the back of our minds and continue with Plan A, returning to the shed problem next week. However, Lynn isn\'t built out of the same "sit down and ponder" mould as me and it was clear that we were going to have to get this job done pronto if we were going to avoid extended shed related edginess.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nrevealed a rather disastrous  With the horrendous weather conditions of the last few days it was never going to be practical to do any work on the plot but we couldn\'t resist a quick trip to witness the effects of the storm. start not \r\n\r\nSeven mice and a toad ran clear of the carpet, or at least the mice ran, the toad just looked aghast and covered up his private parts.', 'A Stormy Kind of Calm', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '300-revision-8', '', '', '2009-11-16 11:43:47', '2009-11-16 10:43:47', '', 300, 'http://www.earthwoman.co.uk/2009/11/16/300-revision-8/', 0, 'revision', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `earth_posts` VALUES (310, 3, '2009-11-16 12:20:01', '2009-11-16 11:20:01', 'A post storm reccy revealed that the wind had completely denuded the shed of its patchy roofing felt but with only 15 mins allocated for the plot visit there was never going to be time enough for a full repair job. \r\n\r\n<p style="float: right; margin-left: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px"><a title="Shed Roof Repair by warriorwomen, on Flickr" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/warriorwomen/4106881738/"><img src="http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2726/4106881738_0bcd2d864b_m.jpg" alt="Shed Roof Repair" width="180" height="240" /></a></p>A shed related edginess cast it’s shadow over our corner of the site as a slight “tension” emerged between the lazy starter-leaver (me) and the task focused completer-finisher (Lynn). I was of the view that without a hammer, a ladder, the time, the inclination or the right clothes, we should put the soon to be rotten shed roof to the back of our minds and continue with Plan A, returning to the shed problem next week. \r\n\r\nLynn isn\'t built out of the same "sit down and ponder over a cup of tea" mould as me and it was clear that we were going to have to get this job done pronto or suffer the consequences.\r\n\r\nPlans were hastily rearranged and after a quick retreat for tools (and a flask of tea) we were back and ready for action.\r\n\r\nI tucked myself well away from the stressy end of the plot and dealt with the rubbish pile while Lynn got up close and personal with the shed. The rubbish pile was the main reason for our planned quick visit, most of it had already gone though – thanks to the committee ladies who had been helping us to dispose of all the crud.  I just had to bag up the few remaining bits of polythene and carpet and evict a few squatters. Seven mice and a toad ran clear of the carpet (at least the mice ran, the toad just looked aghast and covered up his private parts). We’ll have to put “Build Wildlife Haven” on our construction to do list now.\r\n', 'A Stormy Kind of Calm', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '300-revision-9', '', '', '2009-11-16 12:20:01', '2009-11-16 11:20:01', '', 300, 'http://www.earthwoman.co.uk/2009/11/16/300-revision-9/', 0, 'revision', '', 0, ''); 
